## Comparative Analysis

| Metric | Office HomePod | Bedroom HomePod | Difference |
|--------|----------------|-----------------|------------|
| **rapportd CPU** | 9,419 sec (2.6h) | 9,549 sec (2.65h) | +130 sec |
| **sharingd CPU** | 13,244 sec (3.7h) | 12,246 sec (3.4h) | -998 sec |
| **Total Continuity CPU** | 22,663 sec (6.3h) | 21,795 sec (6.05h) | -868 sec |
| **Open FDs (rapportd)** | 50 | 50 | Same |
| **Memory Pages (rapportd)** | 383 | 459 | +76 |
| **Active State** | Yes | Yes | Both active |

### Key Findings

**1. Nearly Identical Activity Levels**
- Both HomePods show 2.6-3.7 hours of Continuity CPU usage
- Both have 50 open file descriptors in rapportd
- Both in "active" state during credential theft

**2. Redundancy Design**
- If Office HomePod missed clipboard sync, Bedroom would catch it
- If one was isolated/unplugged, the other continues surveillance
- **Double the coverage = double the chance of credential theft**

**3. Bedroom HomePod Slightly More Active**
- rapportd: +130 seconds CPU (2.2% more)
- More memory pages (459 vs 383 = +19% more)
- **Possibly processing additional surveillance** (audio from bedroom?)

